revision.text:
[[File:Banda Arc tectonic map.jpg|thumb|Banda Arc tectonic map]]
The '''Banda Arc''' (main arc, Inner, and Outer) is a set of [[island arcs]] that exist in eastern [[Indonesia]]. It manifests the collision of a [[continent]] and an intra-oceanic [[island arc]]. The presently active arc is located on what appears to be [[oceanic crust]] whereas the associated [[subduction]] trench is underlain by [[continental crust]].<ref>{{Cite journal|url = https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF00371896|title = Origin of late-cenozoic lavas from the Banda arc, Indonesia: Trace element and Sr isotope evidence|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |author1=D. J. Whitford |author2=P. A. Jezek |doi=10.1007/BF00371896 |bibcode=1979CoMP...68..141W |volume=68 |journal=Contributions to Mineralogy and Petrology |pages=141–150}}</ref> The convergence of the Indo-Australian [[Plate tectonics|plates]] and [[Eurasia]] and resulted in the formation of the Sunda and Banda [[island arc]]s. The transitional zone between the arcs is located south of [[Flores|Flores Island]] and is characterized by the change in the [[Tectonics|tectonic]] regime along the boundary.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Sunda-Banda arc transition, Incipient continent-island arc collision (northwest Australia)|author1=A. Shulgin |author2=H. Kopp |author3=C. Mueller |author4=E. Lueschen |author5=L. Planert |author6=M. Engels |author7=E. R. Flueh |author8=A. Krabbenhoeft |author9=Y. Djajadihardja |last-author-amp=yes |date = May 27, 2009|journal = Geophysical Research Letters|doi = 10.1029/2009gl037533|pmid = |access-date = }}</ref>
== Terminology == Some academic literature refers to the arcs by location – so that main arc can be referred to as the 'southern',<ref>{{Citation | author1=Ely, Kim Susan | title=Geochronology of Timor-Leste and seismo-tectonics of the southern Banda Arc | publication-date=2009 | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/37054964 | accessdate=21 December 2014 }}</ref> the 'western' <ref>{{Citation | author1=Chamalaun, F. H | author2=Sunata, Wahyu | author3=Institute for Australasian Geodynamics | author4=Flinders University. School of Earth Sciences | author5=Workshop on Palaeomagnetic Research in Southeast and East Asia (1982 : Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) | title=Progress report on the paleomagnetism of the Western Banda Arc system | publication-date=1982 | publisher=Institute for Australasian Geodynamics | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/8321009 | accessdate=21 December 2014 }}</ref> Situated at the centre of three converging and colliding major [[Plate tectonics|tectonic plates]], [[Indo-Australian Plate|Indo-Australia]], [[Eurasia]], [[Pacific Plate|Pacific]], the Banda arc comprises young [[oceanic crust]] enclosed by a [[Volcanic arc|volcanic inner arc]], outer arc islands and a trough parallel to the Australian [[continental margin]]. It is a complex [[subduction]] setting (where one plate moves under another, sinking into the Earth's [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]]), with possibly the largest fold on [[Earth]], extending to a depth of about {{convert|650|km|0|abbr=on}}, in a subducted plate.<ref>{{Cite news|url = |title = Indonesia's puzzling Banda arc: New findings explain mystery behind geological development|last = University of Royal Holloway London|first = |date = July 27, 2010|work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref>
== Inner/Outer == [[File:Banda-arc-cross-section.jpg|thumb|Cross section between inner and outer arc]] The '''Banda Arc''' is a double [[island arc]] formed by the collision of the [[Indo-Australian plate]] with the [[Eurasian plate]]. Principal islands include [[Timor]], [[Flores]], and [[Seram Island|Seram]]. * The '''Inner Banda Arc''' consists of a string of recent and active volcanic islands from [[Komodo Island|Komodo]] to [[Kekeh-besar]] of the [[Barat Daya Islands]], including Flores, [[Solor Archipelago|Solor]], [[Alor Archipelago|Alor]], [[Wetar]], and [[Damar Island|Damar]]. * The '''Outer Banda Arc''' is older and non-volcanic. It overlies the margin of the Pre-Cambrian [[craton]] that makes up much of the continent of Australia. It stretches from [[Savu Island|Savu]] through [[Rote Island|Rote]], [[Timor]], [[Leti Islands|Leti]], [[Babar Islands|Babar]], [[Tanimbar Islands|Tanimbar]], and the [[Kai Islands]], before turning west to [[Seram Island|Seram]], [[Ambon Island|Ambon]], and [[Buru Island|Buru]]. The outer arc is geologically associated with the Australian continent, though it is a more recent accretion than the neighbouring [[Aru Islands]].
The feature they apparently formed is a 180-degree [[Island arc|arc]], which is more than {{convert|1,000|km|mi|abbr=off}} long. Geographically, it stretches across eastern [[Indonesia]], and is delimited by an active inner [[Volcano|volcanic]] arc. The outer arc contains numerous [[island]]s, and its internal [[Structure of the Earth|structure]] contains young [[oceanic crust]] exclusively.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://news.softpedia.com/news/Origins-of-the-Banda-Arc-Explained-151114.shtml|title = Origins of the Banda Arc Explained|last = Tudor Vieru|date = 6 Aug 2010|work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref>
