A '''block and ash flow''' or '''block-and-ash flow''' is a flowing mixture of [[volcanic ash]] and large (>26 cm) angular [[Boulder|blocks]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://volcanoes.usgs.gov/vsc/glossary/block_and_ash_flow.html |title=Glossary - Block and ash flow |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=volcanoes.usgs.gov |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |access-date=22 October 2018 |quote=Flow of ash and angular rock fragments larger than 26 cm or 10 in.}}</ref> commonly formed as result of a [[landslide|gravitational collapse]] of a [[lava dome]] or [[lava flow]].<ref name=encyclovolc2015>{{Cite book|title =Encyclopedia of Volcanoes |chapter= Chapter 54 – Hazards from Pyroclastic Density Currents|url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780123859389000377|publisher = Academic Press|date = 2015|edition=2nd|location = Amsterdam|isbn = 978-0-12-385938-9|pages = 943–956|first = Paul D.|last = Cole|first2 =Augusto |last2 =Neri |first3 =Peter J.|last3 = Baxter|editor-first = Haraldur|editor-last = Sigurdsson|editor-link=Haraldur Sigurdsson}}</ref> Block and ash flows are a type of [[pyroclastic flow]] and as such they form during [[volcanic eruption]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Ui |last1=Tahide |last2=Matsuwo |first2=Norimichi|last3=Sumita |first3=Marit |last4=Fujinawa|first4=Akihiko |date=1999 |title=Generation of block and ash flows during the 1990–1995 eruption of Unzen Volcano, Japan |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0377027398001280 |journal=[[Journal of Volcanology and Geothermal Research]] |volume=89 |issue=1–4 |pages=123–137 |doi=10.1016/S0377-0273(98)00128-0 |access-date=October 22, 2018 }}</ref> In difference to other types of pyroclastic flows block and ash fows do no contain pumice<ref name=Sand2>{{cite web |url=https://www.sandatlas.org/block-and-ash-flow-deposit-in-tenerife/ |title=Block-and-ash flow deposit or lithic breccia? |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Sandsatlas |publisher= |access-date=October 22, 2018 |quote=}}</ref> and the volume of block and ash flow deposits is usually small.<ref name=encyclovolc2015/> Block and ash flows deposits have densities in the range of 1600 to 2000 kg/m<sup>3</sup>, two to five time greater than ash fall deposits.<ref name=encyclovolc2015-ch13>{{Cite book|title =Encyclopedia of Volcanoes |chapter= Chapter 13 – Sizes of Volcanic Eruptions|url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780123859389000377|publisher = Academic Press|date = 2015|edition=2nd|location = Amsterdam|isbn = 978-0-12-385938-9|pages = 257–264|first = David M.|last = Pyle|editor-first = Haraldur|editor-last = Sigurdsson|editor-link=Haraldur Sigurdsson}}</ref> Some blocks in block and ash flow deposits may have thin and shiny coatings of carbon derived from [[charcoal]] formed from vegetation trapped by the flow.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Donoghue |first1=E. |last2=Troll |first2=V.R. |last3=Schwarzkopf |first3=L.M.|last4=Clayton |first4=G.|last5=Goodhue |first5=R. |date=January 1, 2009 |title=Organic block coatings in block-and-ash flow deposits at Merapi Volcano, central Java |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/organic-block-coatings-in-blockandash-flow-deposits-at-merapi-volcano-central-java/658564F6500003A2604466A0BF2A2503 |journal=[[Geological Magazine]] |volume=146 |issue=1 |pages=113–120 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>

Some volcanoes known for their production of block and ash flows in since the 1990s are [[Mount Unzen]] in Japan, [[Mount Merapi]] in Java and [[Soufrière Hills]] in the Lesser Antilles.<ref name=Sand>{{cite web |url=https://www.sandatlas.org/block-and-ash-flow-deposits/#2 |title=Block-and-ash flow deposits |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Sandsatlas |publisher= |access-date=October 22, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>

