{{Other uses|Hesione (mythology)}}
According to the 6th century BC mythographer [[Acusilaus]], '''Hesione''' ([[Help:IPA/English|/hɪˈsaɪ.əniː/]]; [[Ancient Greek]]: Ἡσιονη) was the daughter of [[Oceanus]], the wife of [[Prometheus]] and the mother of [[Deucalion]].<ref>[[Acusilaus]], fr. 34 Fowler (Fowler 2001, [https://books.google.com/books?id=j0nRE4C2WBgC&pg=PA22 p. 22]; Fowler 2013, [https://books.google.com/books?id=scd8AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA113 p. 113]; Freeman, [https://books.google.com/books?id=B75GgVdxYT0C&pg=PA17 p. 17 fragment 33]).</ref> That she was a daughter of Oceanus and wife of Prometheus, was also repeated in [[Aeschylus]]' ''[[Prometheus Bound]]''.<ref>[[Aeschylus]], ''[[Prometheus Bound]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0085.tlg003.perseus-eng1:552-560 552&ndash;560].</ref> She may be identical to '''Pronoia''' (means "care" or "forethought") who was given as Deucalion's mother according to various sources.
