The '''National Environmental Satellite, Data, and Information Service''' (NESDIS) was created by the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA) to operate and manage the United States environmental satellite programs, and manage the data gathered by the [[National Weather Service]] and other government agencies and departments.
==History== In August 1980, the National Earth Satellite Service (NESS) was removed from the Office of Oceanic and Atmospheric Services and became a principal agency line organization in NOAA with an Assistant Administrator who reported directly to the Administrator. This move reflected the increasing importance of satellite observations to NOAA's environmental science and service responsibilities. It was largely precipitated by a decision by the Carter Administration in November 1979 to assign NOAA management responsibility for all civil operational remote sensing from space. NESDIS was formed in 1982 with the merger of NESS and the Environmental Data Service.
NESDIS has managed operational polar orbiting satellites (POES) since 1966. Additionally, NESDIS has managed operational [[geosynchronous satellites]] (GOES) satellites since 1974. New generations of satellites are being developed to succeed the current polar orbiting and geosynchronous satellites: the [[Joint Polar Satellite System]]) and [[GOES-R]]. The first satellite in the GOES-R series is scheduled for launch in October 2016. The launch of JPSS-1 is scheduled for no later than March 2017.
In 1979 NOAA's first [[Polar Operational Environmental Satellites|polar-orbiting environmental satellite]] was launched. Current operational satellites include [[NOAA-15]], [[NOAA-18]], [[NOAA-19]], [[GOES 13]], [[GOES 14]], [[GOES 15]], [[Jason-2]], and [[DSCOVR]]. Since May 1998 NESIDS has operated the [[Defense Meteorological Satellite Program]] (DMSP) satellites on behalf of the [[557th Weather Wing|Air Force Weather Agency]].
==Organization== {{Update|section|reason=the section contains multiple dead links|date=December 2016}} NESDIS's [[National Centers for Environmental Information]] (NCEI) archives data collected by the NOAA, [[U.S. Navy]], [[U.S. Air Force]], the [[Federal Aviation Administration]], and meteorological services around the world. NCEI comprises the Center for Weather and Climate (previously NOAA's [[National Climatic Data Center]]) and the Center for Coasts, Oceans, and Geophysics (a merger of NOAA's [[National Coastal Data Development Center]] (NCDDC), [[National Oceanographic Data Center]] (NODC), and [[National Geophysical Data Center]] (NGDC)).
NESDIS also runs the: * [https://www.nesdis.noaa.gov/OPPA/ Office of Projects, Planning, and Analysis (OPPA)] formerly the Office of Systems Development (OSD) * [https://web.archive.org/web/20131110025715/http://www.oso.noaa.gov/ Office of Satellite Ground Systems (OSGS)] formerly the Office of Satellite Operations (OSO) * [https://web.archive.org/web/20150528155431/http://www.osdpd.noaa.gov/ml/index.html Office of Satellite and Project Operations (OSPO)] formerly the Office of Satellite Data Processing & Distribution (OSDPD) * [http://www.star.nesdis.noaa.gov/star/ Center for Satellite Applications and Research (STAR)] formerly the Office of Research & Applications * [http://www.nesdis.noaa.gov/jpss/ Joint Polar Satellite System Program Office] * [[Geostationary Operational Environmental Satellite|GOES-R]] Program Office * [http://www.nesdisia.noaa.gov/ International & Interagency Affairs Office] * [http://www.space.commerce.gov Office of Space Commercialization] * [http://www.nesdis.noaa.gov/OSAAP/ Office of System Architecture and Advanced Planning (OSAAP)] * [http://coralreef.noaa.gov/ Coral Reef Conservation Program] (CRCP) ** [http://coralreefwatch.noaa.gov/satellite/index.php Coral Reef Watch] (CRW) ** [http://www.coris.noaa.gov/ Coral Reef Information System] (CoRIS)
In 1960 [[TIROS-1]], NOAA's first owned and operated satellite, was launched. In 1983 NOAA assumed operational responsibility for [[Landsat program|Landsat]] satellite system.
