[[File:Erythrura gouldiae -Frankfurt Zoo -black headed-8a-3cp.jpg|thumb|right|250px|alt=Gouldian Finch perched on a twig|The IBA supports a population of endangered Gouldian finches]]
The '''Yinberrie Hills Important Bird Area''' comprise some 1050&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> of rocky, [[tropical savanna]] covered, [[woodland|wooded]] hills in the lower [[Top End]] of the [[Northern Territory]] of [[Australia]]. They lie 45&nbsp;km north of the town of [[Katherine, Northern Territory|Katherine]], and about the same distance south of [[Pine Creek, Northern Territory|Pine Creek]]. The site is important for [[Gouldian finch]]es.
==Description== The site is bounded by [[Nitmiluk National Park]] and the [[Arnhem Land|Arnhem Land Plateau]] in the east. It consists of rolling hills with thin, sandy loam soils overlaid by angular [[Cobble (geology)|cobbles]]. The hills are covered by smooth-barked [[eucalypt]]s with an understorey of native [[grass]]es. They are drained by a network of ephemeral streams which retain water through the [[dry season]] in small, scattered pools. Mean annual rainfall in the area is about 1000&nbsp;mm, falling mainly from December to March. Key features of the habitat for the finches are that the lack of grazing, and few extensive [[wildfire|hot fires]], allow native grasses to seed; the persistent waterholes provide drinking water; the [[tree hollow|cavity]]-bearing trees provide nesting sites; and the perennial grasses on the adjacent lowlands provide seed during the [[wet season]]. Land tenure is primarily [[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal]] freehold land held by the Barnjarn Aboriginal Corporation and Wagiman Aboriginal Land Trust.<ref name=bli>{{cite web |url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sitefactsheet.php?id=24456|title=Yinberrie Hills |work= Sites – Important Bird Areas (IBAs) |publisher=Birdlife International |accessdate=2012-06-28}}</ref>
==Birds== The site has been identified as an [[Important Bird Area]] (IBA) by [[BirdLife International]] principally because it is home to a population of [[endangered species|endangered]] [[Gouldian finch]]es. It also supports [[chestnut-backed buttonquail]]s, [[bush stone-curlew]]s, [[varied lorikeet]]s, [[northern rosella]]s, [[hooded parrot]]s, [[white-gaped honeyeater|white-gaped]], [[yellow-tinted honeyeater|yellow-tinted]], [[bar-breasted honeyeater|bar-breasted]] and [[banded honeyeater]]s, [[masked finch|masked]] and [[long-tailed finch]]es, and [[silver-crowned friarbird]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.birdata.com.au/iba.vm |title=IBA: Yinberrie Hills |accessdate=2011-12-05 |work= Birdata |first= |last= |publisher=Birds Australia |date= }}</ref> Other birds occasionally recorded from the IBA include the [[Australasian bittern]], [[partridge pigeon]], [[yellow-rumped munia]] and the northern subspecies of the [[crested shrike-tit]].<ref name=bli/>
